\begin_layout Problem
(7.5) Calculer la différence d'entropie entre 1g d'azote à température 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}=20°C=293K$
\end_inset

 et pression 1 atm, et 1g d'azote liquide à température 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}=–196°C=77K$
\end_inset

 (le point d'ébullition de l'azote), sous la même pression de 1 atm.
 La chaleur latente de vaporisation de l'azote à pression atmosphérique
 est 200 kJ/kg.
 Considérer l'azote comme un gaz parfait à poids moléculaire 28 et de chaleur
 spécifique molaire de 29.3 J/mol.K indépendante de la température.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First consider the entropy change 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta S_{H}$
\end_inset

 of the heating process from –196°C to 20°C.
 For an ideal gas 
\begin_inset Formula $PV=nRT$
\end_inset

 implies: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
dS_{H} & = & \frac{ncdT}{T}+\frac{P}{T}dV=\frac{ncdT}{T}+\frac{nR}{V}dV\\
\Delta S_{H} & = & nc\int\frac{dT}{T}+nR\int\frac{dV}{V}\\
\Delta S_{H} & = & nc\ln\Big(\frac{T_{2}}{T_{1}}\Big)+nR\ln\Big(\frac{V_{2}}{V_{1}}\Big)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Now consider the entropy change 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta S_{B}$
\end_inset

 of the boiling process:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta S_{B}=\frac{nl^{'}}{T_{1}}=\frac{ml}{T_{1}}=\frac{(0.001kg)(200kJ/kg)}{77K}=0.0026\frac{kJ}{K}=2.6\frac{J}{K}
\]

\end_inset

The number of moles of nitrogen gas 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{2}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n=\frac{m}{M}=\frac{1g}{28g/mol}=\frac{1}{28}
\]

\end_inset

We can find the two volumes using the state equation 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\frac{nRT}{P}$
\end_inset

 noting that the pressure is constant:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V_{1} & = & \frac{nRT_{1}}{P}=\frac{(\frac{1}{28})8.31(77)}{101.3\times10^{3}}=2.26\times10^{-4}m^{3}\\
V_{2} & = & \frac{nRT_{2}}{P}=\frac{(\frac{1}{28})8.31(293)}{101.3\times10^{3}}=8.58\times10^{-4}m^{3}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

So the total entropy difference is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Delta S & = & \Delta S_{B}+\Delta S_{H}\\
 & = & 2.6+nc\ln\Big(\frac{T_{2}}{T_{1}}\Big)+nR\ln\Big(\frac{V_{2}}{V_{1}}\Big)\\
 & = & 2.6+\frac{1}{28}(29.3)\ln\Big(\frac{293}{77}\Big)+\frac{1}{28}(8.31)\ln\Big(\frac{8.58}{2.26}\Big)\\
 & = & 2.6+1.40+0.40\\
\Delta S & = & 4.4\frac{J}{K}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
(7.8) Calculer le changement d'entropie de l'Univers résultant des processus
 suivants.
 La chaleur spécifique du cuivre à pression constante est 385 J kg–1 K–1.
 Dans chaque situation on s'attend suffisamment longtemps pour que le système
 atteint l'équilibre thermique.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\bar under
A.

\series default
\bar default
 Un bloc de cuivre de masse 0.4 kg et température 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}=100ºC=373K$
\end_inset

 est mis dans un lac à température 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}=10ºC=283K$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume that the lake is large enough so that the final temperature of the
 block is 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}=283K$
\end_inset

.
 The entropy change in the block of copper is then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
dS_{Cu} & = & \frac{\delta Q}{T}=\frac{mcdT}{T}\\
\Delta S_{Cu} & = & mc\int\frac{dT}{T}=mc\ln\Big(\frac{T_{2}}{T_{1}}\Big)\\
\Delta S_{Cu} & = & (0.4)(385)\ln\Big(\frac{283}{373}\Big)=-42.5\,\frac{J}{K}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The lake absorbs heat in an (approximately) isothermal process so the entropy
 change in the lake is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Delta S_{lake} & = & \frac{-Q}{T_{2}}=\frac{-mc}{T_{2}}\int_{T_{1}}^{T_{2}}dT=\frac{mc(T_{1}-T_{2})}{T_{2}}\\
\Delta S_{lake} & = & \frac{0.4(385)(373-283)}{283}=49.0\frac{J}{K}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

This means that the entropy change in the universe is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Delta S_{universe} & = & \Delta S_{lake}+\Delta S_{Cu}\\
 & = & 49.0-42.5\\
\Delta S_{universe} & = & +6.5\frac{J}{K}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series bold
\bar under
B.

\bar default
 
\series default
Le même bloc à 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}=10ºC=283K$
\end_inset

 est laissé tomber dans le lac d'une hauteur de 
\begin_inset Formula $h=100m$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that no heat is exchanged between the block and the surrounding lake.
 Thus for the block, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dS_{Cu}=\frac{\delta Q}{T}=0\,\implies\Delta S_{Cu}=0
\]

\end_inset

However, the lake absorbs the kinetic energy of the block.
 Assuming the lake is much larger than the block, it experiences no change
 in internal energy.
 The entropy change of the lake is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
dS_{lake} & = & \frac{\delta Q}{T}=\frac{dU+\delta W}{T}=\frac{\delta W}{T}\\
\Delta S_{lake} & = & \frac{W}{T}=\frac{mgh}{T}\\
\Delta S_{lake} & = & \frac{(0.4)(9.8)(100)}{283}=+1.39\frac{J}{K}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The entropy change in the universe is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta S_{universe}=\Delta S_{lake}+0=1.39\frac{J}{K}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series bold
\bar under
C.

\series default
\bar default
 Deux blocs identiques à températures 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{A}=100ºC=373K$
\end_inset

 et 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{B}=10ºC=283K$
\end_inset

 sont mis en contact dans une enceinte adiabatique isobare de capacité thermique
 négligeable.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The two blocks are isolated from their surroundings, so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta S_{universe}=0+\Delta S_{system}
\]

\end_inset

Heat flows from block A to block B:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Delta S_{system} & = & \Delta S_{A}+\Delta S_{B}\\
 & = & \frac{-Q}{T_{A}}+\frac{Q}{T_{B}}=-Q\Big(\frac{1}{T_{A}}-\frac{1}{T_{B}}\Big)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=|Q_{A}|=|Q_{B}|$
\end_inset

.
 We can find 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 by using the fact that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
|Q_{A}| & = & |Q_{B}|\\
mc(T_{A}-T_{F}) & = & mc(T_{F}-T_{B})\\
T_{A}-T_{F} & = & T_{F}-T_{B}\\
T_{F} & = & \frac{T_{A}+T_{B}}{2}=\frac{373+283}{2}=328K
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Then,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q=|Q_{A}|=mc(T_{A}-T_{F})=0.4(385)(373-328)=6930J
\]

\end_inset

and so
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta S_{universe}=-Q\Big(\frac{1}{T_{A}}-\frac{1}{T_{B}}\Big)=-6390\Big(\frac{1}{373}-\frac{1}{283}\Big)=5.45\frac{J}{K}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
(8.1) Les équations d'état pour un système thermodynamique sont 
\begin_inset Formula $P=aT-b(V-V_{0})$
\end_inset

 et 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\frac{b}{2}(V-V_{0})^{2}+cT$
\end_inset

 où 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 et 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 sont des constantes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\bar under
A.

\series default
\bar default
 Démontrer que ces équations sont consistantes avec les lois de la thermodynamiq
ue (qu'elles satisfont les conditions de consistance).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First we require that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Big(\frac{\partial U}{\partial V}\Big)_{T}=T\Big(\frac{\partial P}{\partial T}\Big)_{V}-P
\]

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Big(\frac{\partial U}{\partial V}\Big)_{T}=b(V-V_{0})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Big(\frac{\partial P}{\partial T}\Big)_{V}=a$
\end_inset

.
 So the right side becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T\Big(\frac{\partial P}{\partial T}\Big)_{V}-P=aT-aT+b(V-V_{0})=b(V-V_{0})=\Big(\frac{\partial U}{\partial V}\Big)_{T}
\]

\end_inset

as needed.
 Now, we calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{V}$
\end_inset

 using
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{V}=\Big(\frac{\partial U}{\partial T}\Big)_{V}=c=constant
\]

\end_inset

Noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Big(\frac{\partial C_{V}}{\partial P}\Big)_{T}=0$
\end_inset

, we want the following condition to be satisfied:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T\Big(\frac{\partial^{2}P}{\partial T^{2}}\Big)_{V}=\Big(\frac{\partial C_{V}}{\partial P}\Big)_{T}=0
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Big(\frac{\partial^{2}P}{\partial T^{2}}\Big)_{V}=0$
\end_inset

, so that condition is satisfied.
 There are no other consistency conditions for this system.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\bar under
B.

\series default
\bar default
 Trouver l'entropie du système.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We know that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Big(\frac{\partial S}{\partial T}\Big)_{V}=\frac{1}{T}\Big(\frac{\partial U}{\partial T}\Big)_{V}=\frac{c}{T}
\]

\end_inset

We also know that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Big(\frac{\partial S}{\partial V}\Big)_{T}=\frac{1}{T}\Bigg(\Big(\frac{\partial U}{\partial V}\Big)_{T}+P\Bigg)=\frac{1}{T}\Big(b(V-V_{0})+aT-b(V-V_{0})\Big)=\frac{aT}{T}=a
\]

\end_inset

Now, the entropy 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $S(T,V)$
\end_inset

, so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
dS & = & \Big(\frac{\partial S}{\partial T}\Big)_{V}dT+\Big(\frac{\partial S}{\partial V}\Big)_{T}dV\\
dS & = & \frac{c}{T}dT+adV\\
S & = & c\int\frac{dT}{T}+a\int dV\\
S(T,V) & = & c\ln(T)+aV+S_{0}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

